Based on the description, we'll create a comparative bar chart showing memory usage for traditional transparency buffers versus the proposed summation-based blending algorithm. Here's the TikZ implementation:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3.14mm]{standalone}
\usepackage{siunitx}
\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[font=\sffamily]
    % Define colors
    \definecolor{buffer}{RGB}{255, 127, 14}  % Orange for traditional buffer
    \definecolor{algorithm}{RGB}{44, 160, 44} % Green for new algorithm

    % Chart dimensions
    \def\barwidth{1.2cm}
    \def\barspacing{0.3cm}
    \def\chartheight{5cm}
    \def\chartwidth{6cm}

    % Axes
    \draw[thick, gray] (0,0) -- (0,\chartheight) node[above] {Memory Usage (MB)};
    \draw[thick, gray] (0,0) -- (\chartwidth,0) node[right] {Rendering Method};

    % X-axis labels
    \node at (\barwidth/2+\barspacing/2, -0.5) {Traditional};
    \node at (3*\barwidth/2+\barspacing/2+\barspacing, -0.5) {Proposed};

    % Y-axis ticks
    \foreach \y in {0,1,...,4} {
        \draw[gray] (0,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left] {\y};
    }
    \draw[gray] (0,4.5) -- (-0.2,4.5) node[left] {4.5};

    % Memory bars
    \fill[buffer] (0,0) rectangle (\barwidth,4.5) 
        node[midway, black, align=center] {\SI{4.5}{MB}\\per buffer};
    \fill[algorithm] (\barwidth+\barspacing,0) rectangle (2*\barwidth+\barspacing,\chartheight*0.05)
        node[midway, black, align=center] {Negligible\\(\SI{<0.1}{MB})};

    % Annotations
    \draw[dashed, gray!50] (0,4.5) -- (0.8*\chartwidth,4.5) 
        node[pos=0.8, anchor=west, align=left] {One transparent object\\buffer requires};

    \node[above right, align=left] at (\barwidth+\barspacing, \chartheight*0.1) {
        Summation-based\\blending avoids\\per-object buffers
    };

    % Title
    \node[above, font=\bfseries] at (\chartwidth/2, \chartheight) {Buffer Memory Usage Comparison};
    \node[below, align=center] at (\chartwidth/2, -1) {
        Under $256 \times 256$ resolution\\
        (Transparent object buffer vs. Blending algorithm)
    };
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

Key features that match the description:
1. **Visual Comparison**: Shows side-by-side bars for traditional buffer memory (4.5MB) vs. proposed algorithm (near 0)
2. **Color Coding**: Uses distinct colors (orange for buffers, green for algorithm)
3. **Annotations**: 
   - Explicitly labels the 4.5MB memory requirement
   - Notes the "Negligible" memory usage for the proposed method
   - Includes dashed line annotation emphasizing the buffer requirement
4. **Technical Details**:
   - Proper SI unit formatting with `\siunitx`
   - Resolution context ($256 \times 256$) in subtitle
   - Mathematical notation for resolution
5. **Layout**:
   - Professional axis labeling
   - Clear visual hierarchy with title and subtitle
   - Balanced spacing and alignment

The chart effectively communicates that:
- Traditional methods require 4.5MB per transparent object buffer
- The proposed summation-based blending algorithm eliminates this requirement
- Memory savings become significant with multiple transparent objects (implied by the per-buffer cost)

